Ralph Reed has long been one of the more polarizing figures in American pol=
itics. As the first executive director of Pat Robertson=E2=80=99s Christian=
 Coalition in the 1990s, he worked on converting the tens of millions of pe=
ople who were swept up in the exploding televangelist movement into reliabl=
e Republican voters. Later, he was born again as a political consultant and=
 lobbyist. His political advocacy group, Faith and Freedom Coalition, has s=
aid it plans to spend $62 million on evangelical voter turnout for the Nove=
mber election.

The fulcrum of that effort, of course, will be the issue of abortion in the=
 post-Roe landscape. After voters showed up in huge numbers in favor of bal=
lot initiatives in Missouri, Ohio, and Kentucky to protect the right to abo=
rtion, Democrats are betting that this works in their favor
come November=E2=80=94not just to guarantee abortion access state-by-state,=
 but to topple a few Republicans while they=E2=80=99re at it, including Don=
ald Trump (whose own position on abortion remains murky).

But if there=E2=80=99s anything I=E2=80=99ve learned about the conservative=
 movement, it=E2=80=99s that they think in decades, not election cycles. An=
d even though abortion has become a mobilizing issue for Democrats, Reed to=
ld me that he believes the pro-choice backlash is a =E2=80=9Csugar high=E2=
=80=9D that will eventually crash. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a limit to the =
number of states that have [initiatives and referendums]=E2=80=9D in their =
constitutions, he said. =E2=80=9CAnd then it=E2=80=99ll be our turn.=E2=80=
=9D Our conversation has been condensed and edited for clarity.

The Abortion Question

Tina Nguyen: Let=E2=80=99s start with an easy, non-controversial topic. Vot=
ers have overwhelmingly turned out to enshrine abortion access in their sta=
te constitutions, and often cite a candidate=E2=80=99s position on the topi=
c as a deciding factor in the voting booth. The issue will be on the ballot=
s in swing states like Colorado and Florida in November. What do you make o=
f the backlash to Dobbs?

Ralph Reed: On the 40th anniversary of Roe, Time magazine had that famous c=
over where they said the feminists won a historic victory with Roe v. Wade.=
 The sub headline was =E2=80=9C... and they=E2=80=99ve been losing ever sin=
ce=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94which was true. From the time of Roe until Dobbs, the f=
eminists in the pro-abortion lobby did nothing but lose. And we began our l=
ong march through the institutions,
through the courts, through Congress, through the presidency, and through s=
tate legislatures, and systematically restricted abortion and protected inn=
ocent human life. My greatest concern is that 40 years from now, somebody=
=E2=80=99s going to write a headline like that about us: that Dobbs was the=
 greatest victory in the history of our movement=E2=80=94and then after tha=
t, all we did was lose. And so the question is, what do we do about that?

I think the answer is that we respond in the post-Dobbs environment exactly=
 the way we did in the post-Roe environment, in the sense that it=E2=80=99s=
 all about state legislative action. The Democrats are the real extremists =
here=E2=80=94and Joe Biden is the real extremist=E2=80=94because they=E2=80=
=99re for abortion on demand. You can debate when [life begins], but for al=
l practical purposes, [they claim that it=E2=80=99s] at any stage of pregna=
ncy, and they want to pay for it with tax dollars=E2=80=94which means repea=
ling the Hyde Amendment,
which Joe Biden supported for 42 years. If you do the polling on this, by t=
he way, the majority of the American people are fine with restrictions, at =
the absolute latest, after the first trimester.

I guess it was in Hillary=E2=80=99s interview with The New York Times that =
created so much buzz, in which she said, =E2=80=9COur formula was always sa=
fe, legal, and rare.=E2=80=9D Remember, Roe was based on a trimester system=
, and the argument was that after the first trimester, it was going to be p=
ossible to restrict, and therefore it would be very rare. And it would be l=
egal, and therefore safe. And she said that her campaign advisors told her,=
 =E2=80=9CYou can=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=98rare=E2=80=99 anymore.=E2=80=9D Th=
at=E2=80=99s when the party transitioned to on-demand, making it paid for u=
nder Medicaid. It=E2=80=99s treated as if it=E2=80=99s a positive good.

Elective abortions paid for under Medicaid, which the Alan Guttmacher Insti=
tute, Planned Parenthood=E2=80=99s research arm, has estimated to have led
to as many as 300,000 additional abortions a year=E2=80=94if you do the pol=
ling on this, our position is a winning position. It=E2=80=99s where the ma=
jority of the American people are. They don=E2=80=99t want unlimited aborti=
on, and they don=E2=80=99t want to pay for [it with] tax dollars. The probl=
em is that in a campaign environment, that=E2=80=99s doing us very little g=
ood, because they=E2=80=99re able to run these ads saying, =E2=80=9CSo and =
so is for a federal ban on abortion.=E2=80=9D And after that, you=E2=80=99r=
e explaining, and when you=E2=80=99re explaining, you=E2=80=99re losing.

We just have to plow through this current environment. President Trump, who=
 will be the nominee, is going to emphasize state legislative action. We sh=
ould emphasize state legislative action. And neither the pro-choice nor the=
 pro-abortion side is going to be able to pass any sweeping federal legisla=
tion anyway.

The pro-abortion movement is enjoying a short-term sugar high with these in=
itiative and referendum victories, but eventually
those will come to an end. Because there=E2=80=99s a limit to the number of=
 states that have initiative and referendum [systems]. And then it=E2=80=99=
ll be our turn. We=E2=80=99ll go state by state and do what we did before D=
obbs.

That sugar high will drive Democrats and pro-choice Republicans out to vote=
 in this election cycle, though. What are G.O.P. candidates saying to you a=
bout how they plan to navigate this environment?

First of all, this has been a highly organic process, worked out between ca=
ndidates, campaign strategists, the party, the pro-life and pro-family move=
ment, all working symbiotically and in a highly organic fashion to arrive a=
t what to do. What you=E2=80=99re seeing is candidates saying either, =E2=
=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t support a federal bill,=E2=80=9D or if they don=E2=80=
=99t say that, they certainly say, =E2=80=9CA federal bill isn=E2=80=99t go=
ing to move anytime soon.=E2=80=9D Steve Daines said that, and he=E2=80=99s=
 the chair of the Senatorial Committee. Mike
Johnson has said that.

The second thing that they say is, =E2=80=9CI support my state. I support m=
y state=E2=80=99s legislation.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s what Rick Scott has =
said in Florida. He said, =E2=80=9CI support the Florida legislation, but t=
here=E2=80=99s not going to be any federal legislation.=E2=80=9D And if you=
 look at the polling, that=E2=80=99s where most voters are in terms of thes=
e initiatives. For candidates, I think you just say what Rubio, Rick Scott,=
 Kari Lake, and others have said: This is abortion on demand, unlimited, at=
 any stage of pregnancy. The good news is that in Florida they need 60 perc=
ent. I=E2=80=99m not saying they can=E2=80=99t get 60 percent, but I can te=
ll you it=E2=80=99s going to be hard.

You don=E2=80=99t think Trump loses trust among evangelicals by declining t=
o back a national ban?

He is going to be given significantly more slack from the evangelical and p=
ro-life voters because of everything that he did to deliver on the life
issue as president. I have to be honest with you, I don=E2=80=99t know that=
 anybody other than Trump would get that running room. He gets that forgive=
ness because he delivered and kept his promises on the courts, on defunding=
 Planned Parenthood. He spoke to the March for Life. Would any other candid=
ate be given that level of deference? I doubt it.

But I think even there, he and his campaign need to proceed with caution. I=
f they try to water down the pro-life plank of the platform at the conventi=
on, I think there will be significant pushback, because that=E2=80=99s sort=
 of the institutional position of the party as opposed to his personal posi=
tion. And the pro-life and pro-family movement has a proprietary interest i=
n that platform plank because they were the ones who got it on the platform=
 to begin with. I don't have any reason to believe, by the way, that that w=
ill happen. But I=E2=80=99m saying I think if that were to happen, it would=
 be highly problematic for the Trump
campaign.

The Israel Issue

A surprising number of Republicans voted against the aid package for Israel=
 in March. Did that vote indicate a trend away from supporting Israel insid=
e the G.O.P., or do you view that as a one-off?

I haven=E2=80=99t talked to every one of them individually. I do know that =
a number of those individuals are strongly pro-Israel, so that=E2=80=99s a =
case that they=E2=80=99re going to have to make to the voters in their dist=
rict. But it doesn=E2=80=99t change the fact that they voted against aid to=
 Israel. That is a fact. It will go on our scorecards, it will go on our vo=
ter guides, and we will report that to evangelical voters.

I think what they were upset about is the fact, as they saw it, the House R=
epublicans were hotboxed and outmaneuvered in allowing the aid packages to =
come to the floor individually so they all could pass. Prior to that, the
only aid package that came to the floor that had passed was the Israel aid =
package. We had already passed it twice before that vote. So I think that=
=E2=80=99s what they were upset about. It was in the context of that vote.

The counterargument, and it would certainly be my counterargument, is that =
even under prior speakers, who operated under the so-called Hastert Rule=E2=
=80=94which was that nothing came to the floor unless a majority of Republi=
can members of Congress supported it=E2=80=94all three of those aid package=
s, individually or together, would have gotten a vote. So I understand why =
they were upset. But the reality is, there was nothing violative of either =
the Hastert Rule or Johnson=E2=80=99s commitments as speaker.

Do you see evangelicals becoming less willing to help Israel if Netanyahu c=
ontinues to prosecute the war in Gaza?

I think they=E2=80=99ll continue to support the current government. I was i=
n Israel in February, and a lot of other evangelical and
faith leaders are going over there now. They=E2=80=99re all going to find o=
ut what I found out, which is the people of Israel are united behind the wa=
r aims articulated by the prime minister, namely that they=E2=80=99re going=
 to defeat Hamas, demilitarize Gaza, and bring about a new leadership and a=
 new culture so that Palestinian children are not being taught in schools i=
n Gaza to hate Jews and kill Jews. Those are the war aims. They=E2=80=99re =
publicly stated. And the Israeli people are united in that.

Faith & Flag

We=E2=80=99re seeing a stronger tie between evangelicalism and conservative=
 politics, but it=E2=80=99s also a fact that church attendance in America i=
s in decline. Do you see evangelicals retaining an influence in public life=
 if they don=E2=80=99t have the numbers?

Well, first of all, that is true, the decline in church attendance among th=
e overall population. But it=E2=80=99s not as true for the electorate. As a=
 share of the vote, evangelicals are at the highest level that=E2=80=99s ev=
er been recorded. So as long as they increase their participation, I=E2=80=
=99m not concerned about them losing influence at all. The African American=
 community, as I believe it, has either just been surpassed, or will be sur=
passed in the next year or two, as the largest minority group in the United=
 States. They=E2=80=99re going to be passed by the Hispanics. I don=E2=80=
=99t think that means
that their influence is going away. Arguably, their influence under Biden i=
s the highest it=E2=80=99s ever been. So it isn=E2=80=99t just your numbers=
 in the electorate. It=E2=80=99s your infrastructure. It=E2=80=99s your abi=
lity to turn the vote out. It=E2=80=99s your ability to influence elected o=
fficials.

And the other thing that I like to remind people is that, unlike gender, et=
hnicity, and age, evangelicals are the only constituency in the electorate =
that grows based on a spiritual conversion. And you can never look at the s=
ize of the evangelical voters in raw numbers, or as a share of the electora=
te, and engage in straight-line reasoning, or extrapolate current trends in=
to the future, because you just don=E2=80=99t know when you're going to hav=
e another spiritual awakening.

I'm not saying this as an advocate or a partisan. Robert W. Fogle, who is a=
 brilliant historian, argues the period roughly from 1975 to 2000 constitut=
es a fourth Great Awakening [a historical term for
American religious revival periods] that it was largely driven by religious=
 broadcasting and by the growth of religious broadcasters on television. A =
number of people who were exposed to the Gospel got involved in the religio=
us right because of television audiences that they became a part of, or act=
ually experienced a spiritual conversion. That=E2=80=99s not that long ago.

There=E2=80=99s no question that Trump is an unusual champion for the relig=
ious right. Have there been changes in evangelical voting behavior that sur=
prised you?

I don=E2=80=99t know if I would say it surprised me, but I didn=E2=80=99t a=
nticipate Trump=E2=80=99s full-throated support for many of the public poli=
cy priorities of evangelical voters. The life issue, Israel, the courts, re=
ligious freedom. It was not a surprise to me because I knew him. I got to k=
now Donald Trump in the 2010-2011 period, we became friends=E2=80=94=E2=80=
=9Ccollaborators=E2=80=9D would probably overstate it=E2=80=94but I stayed =
in touch with him
and he stayed in touch with me. I got to talk to him about these issues. So=
 I was not surprised. But many were.

We=E2=80=99re seeing in our polling, and we=E2=80=99re seeing in exit polls=
, levels of evangelical support for Republican candidates that I frankly ne=
ver thought was possible. I think it is entirely possible that Donald Trump=
 will get a higher share of the evangelical vote than Joe Biden will get of=
 the Black vote.

Really?

He got 84 percent according to the Pew Research organization, in 2020, and =
that matches our post-election poll. I think it could go higher. When [Geor=
gia] Governor Brian Kemp ran for reelection in 2022, he got 91 percent of t=
he vote of self-identified evangelicals. That=E2=80=99s the highest ever re=
corded in any exit poll since exit polling began, for the evangelical vote,=
 for any statewide candidate.

Given Biden=E2=80=99s radicalism on abortion, on gender, and the way he=E2=
=80=99s undermined Israel while they=E2=80=99re
fighting a war, I think it=E2=80=99s possible that Trump is going to get a =
level of support that we=E2=80=99ve never seen a presidential candidate get=
 from evangelical voters.

