          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Last night, Texas R=
epublican <b>Tony Gonzales</b> managed to hang on to his political career a=
fter a ferocious runoff against far-right social media activist <b>Brandon =
Herrera</b>, extending House incumbents=E2=80=99 nearly unbroken streak of =
primary wins. But Gonzales=E2=80=99s razor-thin margin of victory=E2=80=94a=
 mere 407 votes out of 29,639=E2=80=94suggests that institutionalist House =
Republicans like <b>Tom Cole </b>of Oklahoma and<b> Mike Simpson</b> of Ida=
ho have been right to take their primary challenges seriously. Here=E2=80=
=99s how it all went down, and what might come next=E2=80=A6<br/><br/><ul s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0=
;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>T=
ony=E2=80=99s turnaround</i>: Gonzales was perhaps the best-prepared incumb=
ent this cycle, having honed his campaigning and fundraising
chops back when this was a competitive seat, before 2021 redistricting. Gon=
zales ran like his career depended on it, and rightly so: The state=E2=80=
=99s Republican apparatus was mostly aligned against him. Over the last few=
 years, he has <i>infuriated</i> the right, particularly for being the lone=
 Texas House Republican to vote for a 2022 gun control bill in the aftermat=
h of the Uvalde school shooting, which happened in his district.<br/><br/>O=
ne of the most striking items in the Herrera opposition research file was a=
n online video in which he joked about the Holocaust. The clip led to an AI=
PAC-aligned <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnV=
DJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dQeHVkZmttTlBiZ0pRQzduekNZaz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj1VZEgwU0lyUV9NVVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaGU=
rQmVzdCslMjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODUlMkYyOSUyRjI0JTI5XH=
UwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSU=
yslMjg1JTJGNiUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1f=
c291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW5=
0ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo5MDM5Njh9/9cb36acd7efa8=
1116b9dc576894cba9a72eeee23946be6a33f25ffa048ff8bf8" style=3D"color:#d40000=
;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">ad buy</a></u> agains=
t him and raised eyebrows among some House Democratic operatives, who indic=
ated to me they were considering competing for the seat if Herrera had won.
It=E2=80=99s also notable that <b>Donald Trump</b> stayed out of this race,=
 even though he=E2=80=99d endorsed Gonzales in the past. <br/><br/>The race=
 underscores that the House G.O.P. civil war is not happening in a vacuum: =
Democratic operatives are quietly watching the Republican mayhem and lookin=
g for opportunities to expand their limited options for pickups in the fall=
=2E But given Gonzales=E2=80=99s win, i=
t=E2=80=99s likely Democrats will move=
 on from this particular thought experiment. </li><br/><li><i>Cuellar vs. F=
urman</i>: Speaking of pickup opportunities, we now know who Democrat <b>He=
nry Cuellar</b>=E2=80=99s Republican challenger will be in Texas=E2=80=99s =
28th district: <b>Jay Furman</b>. Cuellar, of course, is currently under in=
dictment for corruption, and there <i>could</i> be an opportunity here for =
Republicans. Furman mostly self-funded a shoestring campaign and last repor=
ted about $2,000 in cash on hand, but his F.E.C. reports show a measure of =
political sophistication. <br/><br/>Sure, Cuellar
has a strong local brand and has been a political workhorse in the region f=
or almost 40 years. And much of the corruption drama was already thoroughly=
 litigated when the F.B.I. raided his house ahead of his tough 2022 primary=
, and he outperformed expectations in that general election as well. On the=
 other hand, Cuellar=E2=80=99s got <i>piles </i>of money going out the door=
 toward legal fees.<br/><br/>For now, no major Republican outside groups ha=
ve purchased TV time in the Laredo or San Antonio media markets. If the G.O=
=2EP. doesn=E2=80=99t make a serious play=20=
here in the fall, it would seem log=
ical that recruiting a top-shelf candidate in Laredo will be a top priority=
 for the N.R.C.C. next year. </li></ul></td>
