          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b>We=E2=80=99re se=
eing a stronger tie between evangelicalism and conservative politics, but i=
t=E2=80=99s also a fact that church attendance in America is in decline. Do=
 you see evangelicals retaining an influence in public life if they don=E2=
=80=99t have the numbers?</b><br/><br/>Well, first of all, that is true, th=
e decline in church attendance among the overall population. But it=E2=80=
=99s not as true for the <i>electorate</i>. As a share of the vote, evangel=
icals are at the highest level that=E2=80=99s ever been recorded. So as lon=
g as they increase their participation, I=E2=80=99m not concerned about the=
m losing influence at all. The African American community, as I believe it,=
 has either just been surpassed, or will be surpassed in the next year or t=
wo, as the largest minority group in the United States. They=E2=80=99re goi=
ng to be passed by the Hispanics. I don=E2=80=99t think that means
that their influence is going away. Arguably, their influence under Biden i=
s the highest it=E2=80=99s ever been. So it isn=E2=80=99t just your numbers=
 in the electorate. It=E2=80=99s your infrastructure. It=E2=80=99s your abi=
lity to turn the vote out. It=E2=80=99s your ability to influence elected o=
fficials.<br/><br/>And the other thing that I like to remind people is that=
, unlike gender, ethnicity, and age, evangelicals are the only constituency=
 in the electorate that grows based on a spiritual conversion. And you can =
never look at the size of the evangelical voters in raw numbers, or as a sh=
are of the electorate, and engage in straight-line reasoning, or extrapolat=
e current trends into the future, because you just don=E2=80=99t know when =
you&#39;re going to have another spiritual awakening.<br/><br/>I&#39;m not =
saying this as an advocate or a partisan. <b>Robert W. Fogle</b>, who is a =
brilliant historian, argues the period roughly from 1975 to 2000 constitute=
s a fourth Great Awakening [<i>a historical term for
American religious revival periods</i>] that it was largely driven by relig=
ious broadcasting and by the growth of religious broadcasters on television=
=2E A number of people who were exposed=
 to the Gospel got involved in the rel=
igious right because of television audiences that they became a part of, or=
 actually experienced a spiritual conversion. That=E2=80=99s not that long =
ago.<br/><br/><b>There=E2=80=99s no question that Trump is an unusual champ=
ion for the religious right. Have there been changes in evangelical voting =
behavior that surprised you? </b><br/><br/>I don=E2=80=99t know if I would =
say it surprised me, but I didn=E2=80=99t anticipate Trump=E2=80=99s full-t=
hroated support for many of the public policy priorities of evangelical vot=
ers. The life issue, Israel, the courts, religious freedom. It was not a su=
rprise to <i>me</i> because I knew him. I got to know Donald Trump in the 2=
010-2011 period, we became friends=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Ccollaborators=E2=80=9D =
would probably overstate it=E2=80=94but I stayed in touch with him
and he stayed in touch with me. I got to talk to him about these issues. So=
 I was not surprised. But many were.<br/><br/>We=E2=80=99re seeing in our p=
olling, and we=E2=80=99re seeing in exit polls, levels of evangelical suppo=
rt for Republican candidates that I frankly never thought was possible. I t=
hink it is entirely possible that Donald Trump will get a higher share of t=
he evangelical vote than Joe Biden will get of the Black vote.<br/><br/><b>=
Really? </b><br/><br/>He got 84 percent according to the Pew Research organ=
ization, in 2020, and that matches our post-election poll. I think it could=
 go higher. When [Georgia] Governor <b>Brian</b> <b>Kemp</b> ran for reelec=
tion in 2022, he got 91 percent of the vote of self-identified evangelicals=
=2E That=E2=80=99s the highest ever record=
ed in any exit poll since exit poll=
ing began, for the evangelical vote, for any statewide candidate. <br/><br/=
>Given Biden=E2=80=99s radicalism on abortion, on gender, and the way he=E2=
=80=99s undermined Israel while they=E2=80=99re
fighting a war, I think it=E2=80=99s possible that Trump is going to get a =
level of support that we=E2=80=99ve never seen a presidential candidate get=
 from evangelical voters. <br/></td>
